./runs/20260530-151348-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5019:- Primary-text comparison: MN 22 says the teaching is for crossing and should not be carried after use; the Heart Sutra denies attainment while still relying on Prajnaparamita; Mandukya Upanishad identifies the fourth as the self to be known; Dogen's practice-realization identity treats practice as expression, not a discarded ladder.
./runs/20260530-151348-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5026:This model may over-systematize living traditions. Dogen strains it most because practice-realization is neither retained as a means nor abandoned after reaching a result. The practice is the expression of realization, so the two-axis model may falsely impose a before-and-after sequence. The Heart Sutra also strains it: it denies attainment while ritually preserving the text and practice that enact the denial. A practitioner may report that the method is not possessed, released, or embodied, but simply trusted within a lineage. The raft lens itself may distort the inquiry by favoring tool-use and completion over devotion, inherited belonging, grace, and lifelong communal formation.
./runs/20260530-151348-claude-generate-an-original-lumenary-doctrine-building-/prompt.md:5078:Survived critique from the raft simile, Heart Sutra no-attainment, Mandukya self-recognition, and Dogen practice-realization by narrowing the claim from method completion to post-use relation.
